By definition of the Taylor polynomials,\begin{align*}
T_2(x) &= \sum_{i=0}^{2} \frac{f^{(i)}(a)}{i!}(x-a)^i 
\\ &= \frac{f^{(0)}(a)}{0!}(x-a)^0 + \frac{f^{(1)}(a)}{1!}(x-a)^1 + \frac{f^{(2)}(a)}{2!}(x-a)^2
\\ &= f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + \frac{f''(a)}{2}(x-a)^2\end{align*}

Computing the values of the derivatives of $f$ at 1, we find that
$f(1) = 4 ,\, f'(1) = 12 ,\, f''(1) = 24$. Therefore\begin{align*}
T_2(x) &= f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + \frac{f''(a)}{2}(x-a)^2
\\ &= {\color{blue} 4 + 12(x-1) + 12(x-1)^2}\\ &= {\color{blue} 12x^2 - 12x + 4}\end{align*}
